	(59, 0, 'annonated bibiliography social movement.docx', 23409, 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document', '2\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAnnotated Bibliography: Black Lives Matter\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nManisha Timalsina\n\nAyush Pandey\n\nPresidential Business School\n\nHUM 201b: History of Social Movement\n\nProfessor Hamal\n\nSeptember 10, 2023\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAnnotated Bibliography: Black Lives Matter\n\nThesis Statement- The annotated bibliography emphasizes multiple facets of the Black Lives Matter movement, focusing on its context in history, and inequality in support, illustrating the movement`s key role in the United States of America.\n\nIntroduction\n\nThe following annotated bibliography presents an in-depth analysis of educational resources concerning the Black Lives Matter movement. These articles anticipate the historical roots, sociological consequences, and current relevance of the Black Lives Matter movement, which includes subjects such as injustices based on race in encourage, the movement`s influence on educational institutions, and how it connects with ancient and previous events. They present valuable perspectives into the distinct character of the Black Lives Matter movement (BLM) and its crucially important role in America’s ongoing struggle for racial justice and racial equality.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nFrancis, M. M., & Wright-Rigueur, L. (2021). Black Lives Matter a historical perspective. Annual Review of Law and Social Science, 17(1), 441–458. https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-lawsocsci-122120-100052\n\n\n\n   The Black Lives Matter (BLM) movement is addressed in this article together with its past and present significance, including our particular focus on the movement and the events that occurred in the summer and spring of 2020. It highlights how the protests, which were encouraged by cases of police brutality towards black people, resulted in an enormous change in the People’s opinion of the issue of racial discrimination in society. The paper focuses on the Black activism opposing state-sanctioned violence, which includes murder and outbreaks of violence by law enforcement, which has been around for decades and is an organizing principle for the Black Lives Matter movement. In addition, the article also focuses on the role of black women in the movement by contrasting current activists to historical role models such as Fannie Lou Hamer, and Ella Baker (Francis & Wright-Rigueur, 2021). It has spotlighted the words of decentralized governance and strategies for acquiring authority. \n\n      \n\n     We chose this topic because the article provides historical perspectives and reaches into the starting point of the 20th century and the ancient origins of the Black Lives Matter movement. In addition to the movement’s present state, it focuses on prominent historical people. Also, the article portrays the significant achievements made by Black women throughout the Black Lives Matter movement and this movement facilitates an in-depth awareness of the movement and its evolution.\n\n\n\nDrakulich, K. M., Wozniak, K. H., Hagan, J., & Johnson, D. (2021). Whose lives mattered? How White and Black Americans felt about Black Lives Matter in 2016. Law & Society Review, 55(2), 227–251. https://doi.org/10.1111/lasr.12552\n\n \n\nBlack Americans tend to demonstrate strong support for the Black Lives Matter movement, yet white Americans usually do not. This article claims that it addresses why there exists a disparity in racial makeup since the absence of support among white Americans is surprising. It examines four potential reasons for racial disparities in views regarding Black Lives Matter using evidence from a nationwide survey conducted at the high point of the initial wave of the public’s understanding of the movement. These explanations carry various implications for understanding the importance of these inequalities based on race and represent constructing contrasting arguments made by both advocates and opponents of the movement (Drakulich et al., 2021). Two of the reasons focus on racial bias, while an additional two cover the views regarding the police. The outcome indicates that the racial bias in dealings with police impacted perceptions of the movement in various ways for Black and White Americans.\n\n               \n\nThe relevance and impact on the lives of many black people made us choose this topic.  Policymakers, activists, and others who are passionate about fostering more equality in society would benefit substantially from comprehending the factors that contribute to the disparity in racial makeup in Black Lives Matter support. It sheds light on the obstacles and different difficulties that racial equity movements must have to overcome. \n\n\n\n\n\nBrowning, M. C. (2022). THE EXPLORATION OF HOW BLACK LIVES MATTER IN HIGHER EDUCATION. Journal of Business and Behavioral Sciences, 34(1), 88-98. https://co20hj6zj-mp02-y-https-www-proquest-com.proxy.lirn.net/scholarly-journals/exploration-how-black-lives-matter-higher/docview/2667274931/se-2\n\n\n\n           In 2013, a hashtag on social media called ``Black Lives Matter``(BLM)`` was created in protest of assaults on black people. The outreach expressed over the death of Trevan Martin in 2012 and the subsequent conviction of his murderer became a turning point for the Black Lives Matter movement (Ransby,2018). This study analyzes the Black Lives Matter movement with an attention on how employees, instructors, and students are depicted in the environment of colleges and universities. Personal points of view and opinions are presented via the lived experiences of the current author, a black woman who has worked in a range of positions which includes student, faculty members, and supervisors.\n\n\n      The article provides a distinctive insight by sharing the personal experiences of a black woman who has held several posts within academia. Personal experiences and tales can provide insightful viewpoints on the obstacles as well as chances encountered by individuals within the academic environment is the reason why we chose this article.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMcCoy H. (2020). Black Lives Matter, and Yes, You are Racist: The Parallelism of the Twentieth and Twenty-First Centuries. Child & adolescent social work journal : C & A, 37(5), 463–475. https://doi.org/10.1007/s10560-020-00690-4\n\n          \n\nThis article portrays a battle against the pandemic while dealing with the effects of a recession, state-sanctioned violence against Blacks, racial terror, an increase in racial conflicts encouraged by the president of the United States, and a movement focused on making America recognize and respond to its prevalent racism, anti-Blackness, and state-sanctioned violence against Blacks. This article gives a quick summary of that history and demonstrates how it strongly parallels the present day. It forces White social professionals to recognize their privilege as victims of racism. It serves as an affirmation to social service providers of their ethical obligation to effect change.\n\nI chose this article because the article examines the connection between culture and activism, highlighting how opinions and performances may be effective vehicles for conveying knowledge and fostering social transformation. It gives a spotlight on the various ways in which cultural symbols can be utilized for both political and social objectives.', NULL, '2023-10-09 07:13:47'),
